Change-Id: I263a643988e87124e93a2c8aa7124f943691ead1","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/a86d3765b67b3977ad5afd3ede5561b18b25108e"},{"sha":"76d68c3f2ce78168ffb59f43c39e1ee718c24be1","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[libtpu][PJRT] Use HLO module from serialized executable.

Prior to this change, the caller was responsible for supplying an HLO
module when deserializing a serialized TPU executable, which would be
associated with the resulting executable. This was causing problems
with JAX's new persistent compilation cache, because deserialized
executables would end up with the unoptimized HLO module, instead of
the optimized HLO. This could cause crashes, e.g. when using pjit,
because the optimized module specifies the sharded input/output shapes
but the unoptimized uses the unsharded shapes.

It turns out the optimized module was already included in the
serialized executable (thanks to Qiao for figuring this out). This
change makes the deserialization method use the serialized HLO module
instead of requiring it from the caller.

[{"sha":"59077ac39cc64139f889863081bdb3d0f88d39b6","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[PJRT] Change BufferFromHostBuffer API to support host buffers with arbitrary byte strides.

[XLA:Python] Use byte striding feature to avoid NumPy transposes.

XLA does not support strided on-device arrays. When transferring a NumPy array to an accelerator device, we must remove any non-trivial striding. Currently this work is done synchronously by NumPy.

This change instead performs stride-removal in C++ using the shiny new PJRT transpose library. In many cases, transposition occurs asynchronously on a runtime thread without the GIL held. The PJRT transpose is also faster than NumPy's transpose in all of our existing microbenchmarks. In a future change, we can also parallelize the transposition.

[{"sha":"440639cf18d4a35d055531b14b76d3a0285e05f7","author":{"name":"Haitang Hu","email":"f579da0536377dfe7b0b2da46e481821190fea0d@google.com"},"message":"Supports TPU initialization for any slice.

Instead of directly querying the local devices, we rely on caller to pass in all devices in the distributed setup, e.g., from using a session.
This would allow the global initialization to have a proper full picture of the TPU_SYSTEM and allows the graph rewrite to distribute TPU configuration OPs onto each worker.

Note that we're being conservative here and remains the old branch that initializes without using session. Ideally we can re-evaluate the decision of not using session and see if we can unify the path.

When empty string is given to
`IPython.core.history.extract_hist_ranges`, it will now return a range
corresponding to the whole history of the current session.

everything if given an empty string - which has implications for other
magics like `%save`, `%pastebin`, etc.

Commits that follow this one will introduce that fact to each magic

[{"sha":"e0111ef751ed65406117680efed4e48e0b447503","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"(lite) Extract VerifyFlatbufferAndGetModel to an internal target

Rename VerifyFlatbufferAndGetModel, which was previously a
private subroutine of verifier.cc in an unnamed namespace,
as tflite::internal::VerifyFlatBufferAndGetModel, and move it into
a separate file verifier_internal.cc with a separate header file
verifier_internal.h, with restricted visibility, so that it can
also be used from the Java API JNI code.

This change is in anticipation of adding this function to the shims and changing the Java API code to use the new shims function, rather than just directly calling the
FlatBuffer routines.
